  "prompt": "Why does blue vitriol change its colour from blue to white on heating?",
  "response": "Blue vitriol is another name for copper(II) sulfate pentahydrate, a compound with the formula CuSO\u2084\u00b75H\u2082O. This compound has a characteristic blue color due to the water of crystallization. When blue vitriol is heated, it loses water molecules and becomes anhydrous copper(II) sulfate, which is white or grayish-white in color. The transition can be described in these steps:\n\n1. **Heating**: When heated, the water molecules bonded to the copper(II) sulfate are removed. This process is known as dehydration.\n\n2. **Loss of Water**: The five water molecules that are initially coordinated with the copper ions give blue vitriol its color. Removing these water molecules affects the electronic configuration and hydration sphere around the copper ions, leading to a change in color.\n\n3. **Color Change**: The anhydrous form of copper(II) sulfate is colorless or white because, without water, the electrons in the copper ions are less able to absorb visible light in the same way, resulting in a loss of the blue hue.\n\nThis color change is a common demonstration in chemistry classes to illustrate the principles of hydration and dehydration, as well as the concept of water of crystallization in salts.",
